function widthOfBinaryTree(root) {
    if (!root) return 0;
    let maxWidth = 0;
    const q = [[root, 1]];

    while (q.length) {
        const levelSize = q.length;
        let left = q[0][1];
        let right = left;

        for (let i = 0; i < levelSize; i++) {
            const [node, pos] = q.shift();
            right = pos;

            if (node.left) {
                q.push([node.left, 2 * pos]);
            }
            if (node.right) {
                q.push([node.right, 2 * pos + 1]);
            }
        }
        maxWidth = Math.max(maxWidth, right - left + 1);
    }

    return maxWidth;
}
```

    The algorithm is a BFS (breadth-first search) traversal of the binary tree. We use a queue to store the nodes and their positions in the tree, with the root node at position 1.

For each level of the tree, we find the first and last nodes in the queue, and calculate their widths by subtracting the position of the first node from the position of the last node, adding 1 to get the width of that level. Then, we compare this width to the maximum width seen so far and update the maximum width if needed.

We repeat this process until the whole tree has been traversed, and return the maximum width.

